Republican Strategy of Resistance to Obama's Re-election
The Republican leaders justified their policies by the need to fight forgery in the elections.
However, the Brennan Center considers the latter a myth, claiming that cases of election falsification in the United States are rarer than cases of death from a lightning strike.
In addition, Republican lawyers counted only 300 cases of electoral falsifications in the United States in ten years.
One thing can be said with certainty: these new trends will have a negative impact on the turnout of voters.
In this sense, such actions partially discredit the system of American democracy.
Unlike Canada, U.S. states are responsible for organizing federal elections in the United States.
That is why most state governments have been enacting laws since 2009 that complicate the registration or voting process.
This phenomenon gained new scope after the November 2010 election, which brought Republicans 675 new seats in 26 states.
As a result, 180 bills restricting the right to vote in 41 states were passed in 2011 alone.
The new election laws require the elector to present a photo ID and proof of U.S. citizenship.
In addition, these laws reduce the period of early voting, abolish the right to register an elector on the day of the declaration of will and deprive citizens of the right to vote.
Prior to the 2006 election, no U.S. state had required voters to present a photo ID.
Indiana became the first state to introduce such a requirement.
The U.S. Supreme Court confirmed in 2008 the constitutionality of the law passed in Indiana.
The Republican authorities hastened to spread this practice to other states as well.
Over the past two years, they have initiated bills that require voters to present identity cards with a photo in 34 states.
It is important to note that unlike Quebec, U.S. citizens do not have such a universal identity card as a health insurance card.
In fact, 11% of U.S. citizens, i.e. 21 million people who have reached the age necessary to vote, do not have an identity card with a photo issued by the government body of their state.
In addition, five million new voters in 2012 do not have a similar document.
At the same time, the cost of obtaining the required identity card often exceeds one hundred dollars.
The new restrictions disproportionately affect young people, minorities and low-income people.
In fact, 25% of African-Americans, 15% of people earning less than $35,000, 18% of citizens over the age of 65, and 20% of voters between the ages of 18 and 29 do not have the required photo ID.
But that's not all.
Students - voters who are believed to vote for candidates from Democrats, in several states are not allowed to use the identity card with the photo issued by their educational institution.
However, the same states allow members of fishing and hunting clubs, who vote mostly for Republicans, to use the certificates issued by these clubs to vote for them.
Until 2004, no state had required proof of U.S. citizenship for voting.
For the first time, such a requirement was introduced in Arizona.
As of 2011, more than ten states have passed laws requiring voters to prove they are U.S. citizens.
These measures, of course, are aimed at limiting the voting of Latin American immigrants.
It is estimated that two-thirds of Latin American voters vote in favor of the Democratic Party.
In addition, Republican legislators initiated legislation in 2011 that repeals voter registration on the day of voting in eight states.
They also restricted the right of individuals or groups to provide assistance to those who wish to register.
This restriction did not pass without consequences.
For example, during the 2004 elections, a campaign to register voters helped to list about 10 million citizens.
At the same time, measures taken since 2009 have led to a 17 per cent drop in the number of new voters registered in 2010 compared to 2006.
In addition, Republican legislators in five other states passed laws aimed at reducing the period of early voting.
For example, during the 2008 Florida general election, 33% of voters who voted prematurely were African-American, although the latter accounted for only 13% of the state’s total voter turnout.
The same was true of the Latin American people.
With only 11% of voters, they accounted for 24% of citizens who voted prematurely.
Unlike whites, who make up 76% of the voters, among the early voters were only 46%.
Of course, Democratic legislators and their supporters are actively opposed to the adoption of laws restricting the registration of voters.
Several bills were vetoed by Democratic governors.
The action of the most ambiguous laws was suspended under the intervention of the Attorney General of the United States.
This has allowed us to partially limit the negative effects.
For example, only 16 of the 34 states have enacted laws that require a photo ID.
However, the new rules that came into effect will certainly make it difficult to exercise the right to vote in the 2012 elections.
Critics of the Democrats condemn the bias of the laws that have been passed, seeing in them an obvious focus on influencing the results of the 2012 elections in key states.
Brennan Center’s 2011 report shows that the states that passed these laws represent 171 of the 270 votes needed in the electoral college to win the presidential election.
It is too early to say with confidence that these legislative changes at the electoral system level will have a significant impact on the results of the 2012 presidential election.
There is only one thing that is certain: these new provisions will have a negative impact on the turnout of voters.
In this sense, such actions partially discredit the system of American democracy.
