Preventing disease
Unfortunately, there is no miracle-recipe to prevent cancer.
Despite the progress of scientific research, adherence to a healthy lifestyle remains the best way to reduce the risk of disease.
It is believed that if all people were well fed and moved enough, 30% of cancer cases could be prevented.
“If no one smoked anymore, that number would have increased to at least 50%,” said Andre Bolle, the Canadian Cancer Association’s press secretary.
However, it is estimated that 10% of cancers are caused by heredity.
Several types of cancer remain completely unexplained.
For the Canadian Cancer Association, the fight against smoking remains a priority, despite a reduction in the number of smokers.
Smoking is associated with 85% of lung cancer cases.
It is a risk factor for many others.
It causes enormous damage to people’s health.
“Even today, there are 1.5 million smokers in Quebec,” says Andre Bollere, the secretary of the press.
10 years after quitting smoking, the risk of dying from cancer is halved.
Weighing
According to CAR data, overweight and obesity also contribute to the onset of the disease.
