Higgs boson in detail
Last summer's report that scientists may have been able to detect the Higgs boson caused real agitation - and not without reason.
It is believed that this boson explains the mass of all the particles in the universe, not much or little.
In addition, it is the last particle whose existence has been predicted within the framework of the Standard Model - our best, or at least "incomplete" description of nature and the behavior of matter - but which has previously failed to be detected in an experiential way.
But physicists are not yet fully convinced that this is the Higgs boson.
We know, without a shadow of a doubt, that we are dealing with a really new particle and that it is very similar to the Higgs boson predicted by the Standard Model.
In addition, the new data presented this week at a major physical congress in Kyoto seems to confirm this, although it is not yet sufficient for the full certainty of some data.
Let’s imagine what the Higgs boson is all about, because the chances of making a mistake seem minimal, and let’s see what that means.
There is, in this world, one law that is absolutely inevitable, which says that two things cannot be in the same place at the same time.
There is no way to circumvent this rule, don’t even try too hard, otherwise you will harm yourself.
But while the physics of elementary particles is a rather strange world, it turns out that there is also one law of a similar nature in it: the principle of Pauli's exclusion, which postulates that the two particles cannot occupy the same space at the same time as the "parts" of the same time, not as the "parts" of the same time.
Based on this, physics divides the particles into two categories.
In one corner, we find decent citizens, called fermions, who reasonably obey the Pauli principle.
In another, there are bosons, an ugly band of anarchists who have no respect for anything – at least for this principle, which means that they can be quiet in the same place at the same time.
According to Berkeley's Particle Adventure Laboratory website (by the way), these bosons are divided into two groups: the mesons we will not talk about here, and the "particles of force" through which the bogies are distributed by the main forces of nature and to which the chromosomes are not.
These very bosons, it should be emphasized, not all such exotic beings as you might think.
In fact, if you can read this chronicle, it’s because of one incredibly banal boson: a photon, or “part of light,” which is the “courier” of electromagnetic force.
In fact, when a single particle having an electric charge accelerates or changes direction, it "ruptures" the electromagnetic field in that particular place, roughly like a stone thrown into a pond.
From this "disruption" is born an electromagnetic wave (light, or infrared radiation, or ultraviolet, etc.), and this wave is nothing more than a photon - and therefore one of the bosons "force transmitters".
A more stable field.
The same is true of the Higgs boson, with the only difference that in order for this boson to appear, another field, the Higgs field, must be "broken".
However, the Higgs field is much, much more stable than the electromagnetic field; in order to excite it, it is necessary to achieve very and very high energies, as if it were a frozen pond, the surface of which could only be shaken by a very large stone.
That’s why you need a huge particle accelerator, like the one operated in CERN — the Large Hadron Collider, which is a ring with a diameter of 27 km! — to achieve such huge energies.
An analogy with the electromagnetic field is also useful for explaining the relationship between the Higgs boson and the mass.
In fact, not all particles and not all materials interact with the electromagnetic field.
Some, such as magnets, interact, while others do not: a sheet of paper, for example, will never itself be kept in the refrigerator.
Similarly, not all particles interact with the Higgs field: those that interact have mass, while others (like a photon, by the way) do not.
So, what can "bring" all this research, Ms. Plamondon asks?
In science, they are used to check the correctness of the Standard Model (SM), and this also allows physicists to pinpoint the difference between the results of observations and forecasts of SM.
In addition, some of them passionately yearn for such a discrepancy to be discovered, because the slightest discrepancy can open the door for “new physics” and close some of the Model’s holes.
The latter, it must be said, still has significant drawbacks, offering no explanation for gravity (oh!) or dark matter, which forms about 80% of the universe (oh-oh!).
But no such differences have been found in CERN so far.
Consequences
The benefits of these studies for the everyday life of the average person are more difficult to predict, but it would be a mistake to assume that it does not exist.
Look, in the early 1960s, pioneers of laser research in Bell’s labs couldn’t even guess what revolution their work would bring.
They predicted their applications in science, but nothing more.
In fact, the late physicist Willard Boyle, who worked at the Bell Labs, where the laser was invented in 1960, and who himself developed the first continuous laser (previous ones were pulsed) in 1962, said that the laser was originally considered to be a "grab".
Just imagine...
In addition, the application can be found for the instrumentation accompanying the study.
For example, the same Willard Boyle during his optical research in 1969 developed a small light sensor.
This sensor, although it was not its original purpose, now serves as the “eye” for all digital cameras in the world and earned the 2009 Nobel Prize in Physics.
This, of course, does not mean that the work of the Great Adron Collider will necessarily change our lives, but it only shows, in fact, that everything can be.
