Next to a 93-year-old man who enjoys his last meeting with his family in the yard, lying on his pillows during a toast in his honor, tragically dies a young 36-year-old man surrounded by parents, his wife and two young children and tries everything to make it happen.
“In the past six months, from three to five cocks, they have always been busy with cancer patients under the age of 45,” says Dr. Christian Martel.
53% of the patients admitted to the Victor Gadbua shelter come from home, and 47% from the hospital.
The problem of access to palliative care
It is estimated that 77% of Canadians simply do not have access to palliative care, i.e. care that is provided to alleviate the suffering of patients entering the final stage of their lives, whether at home, in the hospital or in a shelter.
And some institutions, such as the Victor Gadbua shelter and the Society of Palliative Care at the home of the Greater Montreal, specialize more or less exclusively in caring for cancer patients.
It is this huge gap in Quebec’s health care system that causes many doctors – palliative care professionals – to fear the adoption of a law that legalizes euthanasia and assists in suicide.
Starting in October, a manifesto signed by palliative care luminaires, Dr. Balfour Mount and Dr. Bernard Lipuant, is circulating and evidence of their disagreement with such an initiative.
According to Dr. Christian Martel, Quebec’s health care system is not effective enough to ensure the right to high-quality palliative care before the transition to euthanasia is allowed.
Recently, she says, I saw a patient who spent 14 days in the ambulance, in terrible pain, and no one took the necessary measures to relieve them.
I'm afraid patients just want to die because they don't get adequate care.
At the same time, many oncologists try to save patients until the last day, despite pessimistic forecasts.
The hopes of survival for Ellen Richard were already minimal by the time she stopped exhausting chemotherapy.
When I told my oncologist that I was stopping treatment, she told me that she was sorry that I was stopping the fight.
She told me that my days were numbered!
There is no almighty care
Dr. Martel believes that 90% of patients who request death are grateful to the medical staff for not meeting their request after the palliative care team eases their pain.
However, it should be noted that palliative care is not absolutely all-powerful in the fight against pain.
According to Elsie Monroe, director of palliative care at the Greater Montreal Society of Palliative Care, patients are not susceptible to analgesia in 8% of cases.
At the very end of life, doctors often resort to palliative sedation, in which the patient sleeps until his death, either from time to time, or permanently.
We can no longer pretend that we are not aware of this suffering.
More and more often, patients who fail to relieve pain will be able to have access to palliative sedation.
Patients who suffer from pain always say the same phrase: “I want to die.”
But it doesn’t necessarily mean “I want to be euthanized,” it means “I want to be easier.”
