In addition, as is often the case with these technologies, the political vision is obvious: the belief that the current currency system, consisting of banking monopolies, leads to financial crises.
In fact, Bitcoin, invented by Satoshi Nakamoto (a pseudonym), is simultaneously a virtual currency (but converted into dollars, euros...) and a protected BitTorrent-type exchange protocol that allows file sharing between participants of the same level.
About 200,000 operations have already been registered with 15,000 computers on the network.
Several thousand websites accept bitcoins to make donations or as a means of payment.
The bitcoin price, reaching a maximum of $30 (23 euros) in June 2011, fell to $2, five months later, before returning today to about ten dollars (the rates are listed on bitcoincharts.com).
There is nothing special compared to the world exchange of real money or financial products.
However, the European Central Bank (ECB) in its report on virtual currency, published in October, was interested in this system.
He describes bitcoin as “the most successful virtual currency,” “competitive with the dollar or euro,” and “similar to conventional currencies.”
Bitcoin differs from other types of virtual currencies, such as “credits” used to promote in a video game, which are earned during the game or which can be purchased (and sometimes exchanged).
The social network Facebook has also developed a similar system.
But exchange operations are always controlled and processed by any central authority.
In Bitcoin, all nodes of the network are simultaneously accountants, auditors, currency issuers, buyers and sellers.
How does this network work?
Every transaction between two users actually takes place between two e-mail addresses, just like an e-mail.
Only for each new payment, the user can choose a different address, thus ensuring anonymity.
The set of information related to this transaction is signed electronically, using a dual-key encryption system.
The network can also verify the authenticity of the transaction.
Thanks to the contents of the file, it is possible to check that the bitcoins used in the transaction actually exist in a public account book sent across the network.
The key step is to register a new transaction in this book.
It passes through the solution of a mathematical problem sent to computers, which, as a temporary central bank, is given the privilege of adding this new line.
This is the phase of hashing a file, i.e. converting a large file into a digital signature, short and unique.
Computers “take” a new transaction and add a number to it before “hashing” everything together.
The goal is to find a number that will give a unique digital signature (many zeros at the beginning).
Once this number is found, other nodes can easily verify that it is correct.
The transaction thus becomes inextricably linked to the chain of all other transactions; any modification will change the digital signature.
If a user wanted to pay twice with the same money in order to cheat very quickly (in less than ten minutes), only one of these two transactions would be confirmed by the network – and the other would remain unconfirmed, as they have different electronic signatures.
The computer that solves the problem receives 50 bitcoins.
To avoid inflation, the reward is regularly split in half, probably by the end of 2012.
The number of bitcoins in circulation is therefore limited to 21 million, but they are divided to one hundred million, leaving a further reserve.
The complexity of the task also increases with the increase in computing capacity.
The life of the network has already experienced ups and downs.
Sites that provide Bitcoin services were under attack, and bitcoins were stolen from the reserves.
“The defect used does not concern the protocol itself,” says Pierre Nuaz, who recently launched Paymium, a company that makes payments with real money using the Bitcoin network.
The ECB also reported the possibility of money laundering through this anonymous service.
However, cash also has this disadvantage as well.
Big players, such as Wikipedia, refuse to accept donations of this kind.
Others, such as the WordPress blogging platform, allow them.
Recently, Adi Shamir and Dorit Ron of the Weizmann Institute in Israel analyzed the account book and found that almost 80% of bitcoins are not in circulation.
The "Gigant Sale" was announced in November.
“Thirty thousand dollars have been exchanged,” says Yon Holmkvist, who works at Coinabul, which is engaged in the conversion of bitcoins to gold.
Pierre Nuaz, another author of the manual on this currency, firmly believes in the potential of this technology as an operating network.
Its system, Paytunia, is the equivalent of a credit card (in real money) or contactless payment over a mobile phone, but it uses Bitcoin to check transactions, which makes it cheaper.
The owner has better control of his personal data and can thus be anonymous.
The system is simple to implement for entrepreneurs who do not need to install new devices or software.
All it takes is to provide an address that can be "photographed and recognized" by phone, Pierre Nuaz clarifies, confirming that he already has thousands of users.
There is a general tendency to revise hierarchical systems in favor of more horizontal ones.
“Before Bitcoin is confirmed, it will take some time, but 2013 could be a turning point,” he predicts.
In its report, the ECB proposes, by the way, to reconsider the various risks that are considered to be elevated today, in the event of the success of this system.
