Difficult Births of the Constitution of Egypt
This is a risky new step by President Mohammed Mursi.
While Egypt is divided more than ever on the issue of a constitutional declaration that temporarily gives it extraordinary powers, it has decided to play va-bank.
Surprisingly, he announced on Wednesday that the Constituent Assembly would vote on the final text the next day.
Exactly a week ago, the Head of State gave the Assembly two additional months to complete the work.
It is almost two years since Egypt relies on a preliminary text, which has been amended several times, which weakens institutional stability and leads to legal contradictions.
This new initiative has only intensified the division of the country.
In the opinion of his opponents, the President persists in his “autocratic madness”, continuing to “break this word” and “deprive the right.”
In the camp, his followers are convinced that this is a way to end the institutional and political crisis by accelerating the transition process.
The referendum must be held within fifteen days.
A very short period of time, which causes the Brothers to abandon their intention to explain to the Egyptians the text, article by article.
For the president, it is also a way to restore public and democratic legitimacy, while discontent is raging across the country.
Mohammad Morsi seems to be convinced that the Egyptians will vote positively, as he said in an interview with the American weekly Time.
Especially since the call for an accelerated vote resembles an ultimatum to the Egyptian people: “Either you vote for my text, or I leave me extraordinary powers,” which are supposed to be completed after the adoption of the Constitution.
In this strange atmosphere, 85 members of the Constituent Assembly, mostly Islamists, voted for the text yesterday.
Most liberals have not responded to the challenge.
In mid-November, shortly before the constitutional declaration, they knocked on the door, feeling unable to express their opinion.
Representatives of human rights defenders, religious minorities or civil society did the same.
In order to achieve the necessary quorum, 11 people, spare participants, were hastily added yesterday morning.
Some are very close to the Muslim Brotherhood.
It is not surprising that in most cases the articles were voted unanimously.
The commentators, by the way, were pleased with the fact that one of the few differences of the day arose around... time for prayer, as some members of the committee considered that the clocks of the Constituent Assembly were incorrectly set.
The text, on which the vote was held yesterday, consists of 234 articles.
The object of general attention, article 2 ultimately remained an identical article from the 1971 Constitution, stating that “the principles of sharia are the main source of law.”
Salafist parties, for which the implementation of Islamic law is one of the main demands, hoped to replace the "principles" with the "rules" that would allow for their more stringent application.
For Islamists, the fact that this article has not been amended is a testament to their goodwill and respect for other members of Egyptian society.
“Hypocrisy,” replied the liberals, who see only a pier in this.
Because, in their opinion, the Islamization of the Constitution takes place through other articles.
They refer in particular to article 220, which gives the University of Al-Azhar an advisory role, in particular in verifying compliance with Sharia law.
According to Egypt expert Sophie Pomier, this is alarming, because "people who are destined to make decisions are not elected and have no democratic legitimacy."
We can observe the birth of theocracy.”
Many liberals, moreover, are agitated by the fact that the next rector of this university seems to be far less moderate than the current one.
“At the moment, there is no specific religious intervention.
With this constitution, we remain within the framework of civil law.
Most of the lawyers who worked on this text are not ultimatums, but people with university education, some of whom were trained in the French system,” says Alexis Bloe, who is preparing a thesis on the Egyptian constitutional transition.
But he acknowledges that “around article 220 there may be ambiguity, since the terms used in it are borrowed from religious vocabulary.
This applies in particular to the "fiqh" [Islamic jurisprudence, cf. ed.].
And in the future, the question may arise, how competent the civil judges are to make decisions about it.”
In addition to its religious aspect, the text adopted yesterday is subject to criticism, as it gives broad powers to the President of the Republic.
The Muslim brothers claim that they have been significantly reduced compared to what they were under the old regime.
Another point of contention: the powers of the army.
In accordance with the wishes of the military, consideration of the defense budget will take place not in the Parliament, but in the National Defense Council.
