Poland and the Space.
Last week, at the meeting of the ministers of the European Space Agency, Poland was accepted as the second country of the former Eastern Bloc (after the Czech Republic, which became a full member of the ESA on 12 September 2008).
Poland began close cooperation with ECA in 1994 and during the following years took an active part in a number of ECA projects.
But Poland’s journey to space began much earlier.
Even before the Second World War, Polish enthusiasts were engaged in spaceflights, but this was not always met with understanding.
I recall, for example, the lecture of A. Sternfeld, who on December 6, 1933, presented at the Warsaw Astronomical Observatory an idea from his groundbreaking work “Introduction to Space”.
The ideas of the young engineer (1905) left the audience indifferent, after several years Sternfeld recalled that only Dr. Jan Gadomsky was interested in his work.
In 1934, in France, Sternfeld won the Robert Esso Peltry and André Louis Hirsch Prize for "Introduction to Space."
Dr. Yan Gadomsky (1899-1966), mentioned above, later became a great propagandist of astronomy and space science.
He published hundreds of articles in Polish journals and wrote a number of books devoted to these scientific disciplines.
Gadomsky became a world-famous propagandist of space science, and his contribution was appreciated by the fact that one of the craters on the reverse side of the Moon was named in his honor.
As early as 1925, a railway trench was built in Poland, equipped with a rocket engine.
Unfortunately, the author of this idea remained unknown, as well as the details of the project.
It is not even clear whether a rocket had to be used for accelerating or braking the truck.
The information about this drill is only known from the press of that era.
Since 1933, Polish artillery has begun to think about missiles.
The study was carried out by the Armament Technology Section in cooperation with Professors Mechislav Wolfke and Gustav Mokzicki.
From the surviving materials it can be seen that the studies have reached the stage of practical testing.
But with the arrival of the German troops, the work was interrupted.
In 1937, the idea of a photoelectric fighter rocket, proposed by the engineer Rogozinsky, appeared in the specialized press, and the following year the work "Air torpedo and aeronautical missile-bomb" by Lelyva-Khivoblotsky.
Both projects were designed for military use of rocket engines.
Before the war, all the projects for the military use of missile technology were carried out by the Temporary Scientific Advisory Committee (Tymczasowy Komitet Doradczo-Naukowy), which coordinated all the work.
The Committee was established in 1937, but after two years of work the work was completed due to the beginning of the war.
The next scientific work on space science appeared in the Polish press after the war, thanks to the work of the Polish Society of Astronautics (Polskie Towarzystwo Astronautyczne).
For the first time about society is mentioned in the November 1954 issue of the magazine "Problems", which publishes four volume articles on astronautics.
In one of them, Professor M. Subotovich proposed to organize a society that would be engaged in space science.
At the time, artificial satellite projects were already gaining momentum, and it was clear that space research was a promising industry.
Since the beginning of 1956, the Polish Astronautical Society (POA) has been trying to join the International Federation of Astronautics (founded in 1951), and already in the autumn of the POA became its actual member.
And the following year, the first chairman of the POA Kazimez Zarankevich (1902 - 1959) became the deputy chairman of the International Federation of Astronautics.
He remained in that position until his own death, which occurred in 1959.
Since 1956, POA has made a significant contribution to the development of the highly successful RM (Rakieta Meteorologiczna), which became the first Polish rocket to carry out scientific research.
The first RM-1 was completed in 1957, and the first launch took place on October 10, 1958.
The rocket, capable of exceeding a distance of 1800 m, was about 80 cm long, and its weight was less than 5 kg.
Subsequently, an improved version of the RM-1A was built, and in the summer of 1959 tests of the two-stage missile RM-2 were carried out in the Bled desert.
The rocket was about 1.4 m long and weighed about 11.5 kg.
The next version of the missile was already able to do real scientific work - the missile RM-34 could exceed 14.5 km, and its task was to observe high winds.
In 1962, however, further development was halted.
The successor to the first RM was the Meteor-1 rocket, developed between 1962 and 1965.
The rocket was designed as a two-stage, its total length was 510 cm, and its initial weight - 32.5 kg.
Three types (designated as Meteor-1A, -1B and -1C) were developed, which differed in the size of the camera for scientific equipment.
The Meteor-1A rocket had a volume of 0.4 liters, Meteor-1B - 0.34 liters, and Meteor-1C - 0.62 liters.
The maximum flight distance for all three types was 37 km.
Between 1965 and 1968, the Meteor-2 rocket was developed at the Aviation Institute, and its first flight tests began in October 1970.
The Meteor-2 rocket with a starting weight of 380 kg was able to take a payload of 10 kg to a height of about 60 km.
Later versions of Meteor-2N and Meteor-3 were built.
It is also worth mentioning the accession of Poland to KOSPAR (Space Research Committee) in 1960 and the establishment of the national KOSPAR committee two years later.
In addition, within the framework of the Intercosmos program, Poland participated in space exploration on Soviet artificial satellites, and in 1978 the Polish pilot Miroslav Hermashevsky became the second intercosmonaut after Vladimir Remek.
