In November 1979, a mob of Islamist demonstrators seized the U.S. Embassy in Tehran and took 52 diplomats hostage.
They were to be released in exchange for the overthrown Shah Mohammed Reza Pehlevi, who fled after the revolution in the United States, who had been the patron of his regime for decades.
For the U.S. administration, the positive outcome of the situation was not expected - it could not afford to throw the chess overboard, because it could fundamentally undermine the trust of the allies in other countries.
However, to achieve the release of hostages in Iran, where the revolution led to the establishment of a theocratic regime, it was not able.
It was a blow to the prestige of the United States, which was later reinforced by an unsuccessful attempt to free the hostages by force.
The detainees were finally released 444 days later, after negotiations with the government of Algeria.
Their fate has caused a wave of solidarity and anti-Iranian sentiments at home.
The defeat in Iran greatly contributed to Jimmy Carter's defeat in the 1980 presidential election, which ended with the election of Ronald Reagan.
The film, directed by actor Ben Affleck, "Operation Argo" describes one of the episodes of the story that brought America small victories.
Shortly before the occupation of the embassy, six workers managed to escape.
After a difficult period, they completed their journey to the Embassy of Canada residence.
The CIA, in cooperation with the Canadian authorities, managed to get them out of Iran, helped by an extravagant cover-up legend, according to which they went on Canadian passports as members of the filming team, looking in the country for a place to shoot science fiction.
Combination of genres
The plan, which was invented by evacuation expert Tony Mendes, required cooperation from Hollywood.
In order for the legend to be reliable, specialized magazines wrote about the project of the film, held press conferences, the fictional production company had a real office.
The details of the operation have long been kept secret, a film based on the memoirs of Tony Mendes.
The film Affleck is a special combination of several genres.
On the one hand, a real political thriller, the so-called "film-cinopus", a story of a successful plot, affairs - an example can be a number of films about Oshen's friends.
The film is constantly changing moods - on the one hand, documentary scenes from Tehran (the titles show iconic historical photographs of events and how the same situations were demonstrated in the film - there are no big differences in this).
On the other hand, lightened Hollywood passages intersecting with irony and moderate exaggeration.
And then scenes from CIA headquarters and other institutions - men in costumes discuss the situation at the negotiating tables, on the staircases of institutions, by phone ...
Ben Affleck has been able to re-start his career.
He became a well-respected director, and his play ceased to be a subject of laughter.
"Operation Argo" is his third feature film, after the dark detective Farewell, Baby, Farewell (2007) and the thriller "City" (2010).
At the same time, it is Affleck’s first film not filmed in the director’s hometown of Boston.
The feeling of the atmosphere of the place refers to the qualities that have elevated the director’s earlier films above the Hollywood standard.
And Affleck shows it in Argo, where Tehran "plays" Canada.
The best scenes in the film take place in the streets, while reconstructing real events - the introductory scenes of the fall of the embassy impress with their clarity, which also conveys the emotions of confusion and unforeseenness that arise when the story suddenly changes somewhere.
A similar effect is achieved by Affleck and his colleagues in fictional scenes (a fake headquarters in the Tehran bazaar).
There are too many processes in too many places.
The director had to deal with the fact that the narrative does not imply many exciting scenes of cinematic significance.
He works quite successfully with this few, sometimes he comes up with something - there it all comes out not so elegant (a scene in which a phone call in America prevents an impending crisis at the airport of Tehran, and a chase on the take-off runway).
The disadvantage of Argo is the dispersion associated with the need to show too many events in too many places.
Alan Arkin and John Goodman as Hollywood colleagues are indeed very charming, but their characters would have deserved more space, and they are by no means the only ones in the film.
Affleck’s film lacks a bit of drama, it’s a film that can be watched with moderate interest, evaluating the production and retro style that recreates the thrillers of the seventies.
But it's hard to catch.
