But I ask myself, why do we have another library today?
Everyone has the Internet, iPad and e-books.
Now no one goes to such old-fashioned libraries voluntarily, right?
Spijkenisse, an unattractive sleeping town near Rotterdam, holds an unusual record.
Its population of 80,000 people has the lowest level of education in the Netherlands.
To combat this annoying circumstance a few years ago, it was decided to contribute to the general education and build seven imaginary bridges, which are depicted on euro banknotes, in the form of painted miniatures made of iron concrete.
The success of this educational initiative was modest.
And then the fathers of the city realized that they had only one chance to overcome the statistics: to build a library here!
Vinnie Maas of the Rotterdam architectural bureau MVRDV, a master of bold column diagrams and author of clever, sometimes even cynical structures, dealt with the task with his usual indistinctness and appeared at a competitive audition of books in 2003.
And while the jury members were puzzled and squeezed with their shoulders, the daring Maas made from his original gift a pyramid of size and ended his speech in defense of his project with the following words: "Dear citizens!"
Here's my suggestion: The Book Mountain in Spijkenisse, the so-called Buchenberg!
Nine years later, this mountain, worth 30 million euros, has grown.
It is part of the revitalization project, which also includes an underground garage, supermarket, post office and several adjacent residential houses and townhouses for a total of 50 apartments.
At the beginning of November, Book Mountain was awarded the second prize of the competition "Best Library of the Netherlands 2012".
The project also participates in the national Dutch competition for wooden structures in 2012.
Thus, the faceless suburb, which had previously been able to offer nothing but a postmodernist pedestrian zone and an amazingly unpretentious town hall, whose white facades suggest a dairy farm, became richer in one modern work of architecture.
But most importantly, in Spijkenisse, the first in the history of this town was a public building of cultural purpose.
A long way to the book
First impression: the book Eldorado under the cheese cap.
There is only one lift in the center of the mountain range, because real fans of architecture and reading will prefer to explore this area on foot.
Glassed on all sides of the room - light and easily visible, floors made of burnt brick and elegant street lights infallibly create the feeling of a public urban square.
The urban environment is perfectly restored.
The look is involuntarily looking for couches, dogs and playing football for boys and girls.
And everywhere - books, books, books.
“Usually the book shelves stand along the facades, and in the middle there is a large dark room, usually uncomfortable and faceless,” says Vinnie Maas.
We put the classic configuration of the space from the foot to the head and pulled out the reading area from the inside out.
The interior of the book mountain is used skillfully: the center has offices, an internet library, a chess club, an environmental center and technical facilities.
Especially happy are black book shelves, which serve as wall decorations, parapets, stair railings.
Their appearance, texture and smell are unusual.
Even intrigued architects and engineers-builders get lost in guessing what kind of unknown material it is.
“We tried to work with secondary materials,” explains Jop Trawborst, project manager representing the Spijkenisse community, in line with the standards.
And one time at a single farm in Friesland, we encountered a suitable by-product of agriculture.
For many years, in greenhouses and fields in the Netherlands, artificial fiber material of millimetre thickness has been used as a root padding.
It is cheap and saves time.
Thin textile serves one or two seasons, after which it can be thrown away.
For the library, this canvas - for the first time in such volumes - was pressed into a panel four centimeters thick.
Under the influence of heat and pressure, the so-called landbauplastic (KLP) turns into a dark, uniform, durable material, smelling a little like a new car and a little sneakers.
There are 105 steps to the top.
Anyone who crosses the nearly 500-metre-long path will be rewarded in a literary cafe not only with fantastic views of the city, but also with Dutch croquettes and wooden chips in pots.
They care about the atmosphere, and above all about the correct humidity of the air on the literary mountain.
Expenses for a new soul
“It’s hard to believe, but this building, despite the many glass surfaces, is an environmentally-exemplary project,” Trouborst says.
For its heating and cooling, the heat of the earth is used.
Although the Book Mountain stands under a glass cap, even on clear days the sun only comes in for a short time.
Wide adhesive wood farms, located perpendicular to the glass fa<0xC3><0xA7>ade, give shade and take on most of the sun's rays.
The climate in the room is very pleasant.
The rest of the protection is provided by fully automatic roller blinds.
