Norwegian rayfish: the world's most stinky fish?
With a population of 5 million, Norway has one of the highest standards of living not only in Europe, but also in the world.
Is it possible that the secret of this country’s success is somehow related to the local addiction to one extremely vicious fish dish?
Take a few ripened pieces of cheese.
Place them in a pile of dirty and sweaty sports clothes.
Leave them there for a week.
You will get the scent of raccoon - one of the most famous Norwegian delicacies.
I'm in a small town called Fagernes, three hours' drive from Oslo.
Around the snow-covered picturesque sights. It is very beautiful, but in the air pours an indestructible characteristic smell.
Rakfish is a forel, sprinkled with salt and roasted in water for up to a year, depending on what kind of shower you need to achieve.
As the twilight thickens and cools, the crowds of Norwegians gather for a festival in Fagernes, dedicated to this very, let’s say, exciting dish.
"They eat raw and drink a can of aquavit, a local mint of vodka," explains Howard Halvarsen, a local firefighter in the profession and co-chairmanship of the "Racfisk General", who leads the festival.
Everywhere around us, people eat small cubes of fish and drink it with countless portions of liquor.
“Someone prefers aquavit rather than racfish,” says Howard.
This drink is able to break the smell.
I'll try a couple of pieces.
If you can carry a piece under your nose, then everything is not so bad - it is little different from the portion of sushi that you have been carrying in the bus for a long time.
Rakfisk is a Norwegian product from completely different times, times of poverty, when, even before the appearance of the refrigerators, fish were soaked in autumn in hermetically sealed barrels with salt water.
Then in the deep winter, when the fish had already well and thoroughly fertilized, it was extracted and, muted by the perception of alcohol, consumed in food.
In memory of the last generation, the fact that thousands of Norwegians were forced to leave their country in search of work and emigrate, mainly to the United States.
Now the population is growing rapidly – more than 13% of immigrants are involved in jobs, high salaries and a developed social security system.
Residents of Sweden (an old rival, and not so long ago and a much more prosperous neighbor) come here to work.
Rakfisk is perceived as an important symbol, an indispensable, albeit somewhat evil element of Norway’s past.
This is one of the most expensive local dishes.
On the other hand, here everything is expensive - a small glass of beer or a sandwich will cost you <0xC2><0xA3>9 ($14).
Norway rarely appears in the world’s news, and most of the country’s residents seem to do so.
People here are still reluctant to mention the name of Anders Breivik, a racist and right-wing extremist who shot and killed 77 men, women and children last year.
Without mentioning his name, the attack is called "the 22nd of July".
It is very difficult for Norwegians to believe that in their peaceful country one of their fellow citizens was capable of such atrocities and murders.
At the heart of today’s well-being is Norway’s growth (since the early 1970s) one of the largest oil and gas industries in the world.
“However, oil is not the only reason for our prosperity,” says Anna, our waitress, who wears trays with a hard-wearing raccoon, a woman with long light hair and strikingly blue eyes, the embodiment of Nordic well-being.
We are a people, as you call it, reasonable.
Like most Norwegians, she speaks very well in English.
We don't like to show off, we don't brag.
Norway is very careful about its oil – most of the oil and gas industry’s revenues are invested in a special fund created for the benefit of future generations.
In the years leading up to the global financial crisis, when everyone was squandered with money they didn’t have, Norway carefully counted all the costs.
“As long as you can go skiing in the winter and go hiking in the summer, that’s enough for happiness,” says Anna.
"And there's a rakfish," she adds with carefree laughter.
I'm standing in the snow in a queue for some food - the raksha is enough for me.
Here's a hamburger with salmon - it's definitely exotic, delicious juicy meat.
But in the evening we have even more of the same fish with an unforgettable smell.
In my hotel there is a special dinner dedicated to raccoon, during which the visitors determine by voting the best or perhaps the most fragrant fish.
There is a direct telecast, in which they show the leader in a butterfly tie, surrounded by plates with racfish.
It's like the Eurovision Song Contest.
"So, Thor-Jurgen, what did you rate the best fish out there in the mountains?"
"Yes, Howard, here's our assessment."
Everyone laughs and applauds.
Someone falls off a chair, maybe by crossing an aquavit.
Or maybe just sniffing out the smell of this fish.
Mexican President Enrique Pe<0xC3><0xB1>a Nieto has a difficult career ahead of him.
As Mexico’s newly elected president, Enrique Penya Nieto, prepares to take office, BBC correspondent Will Grant invites us to take a look at the difficulties he faces and the mixed expectations of his country’s population.
The traffic in Mexico City is now in a particularly bad state.
This city is overcrowded with transport and at the best time, and since Monday steel fences were built, intersecting several key highways to the capital and causing chaos on the roads.
