Bradley Manning has not complained of ill-treatment, the indictment says.
Prosecutors are trying to disprove Bradley Manning's statements about poor conditions of detention.
During the hearing, increased attention was paid to Manning’s stay in a military prison in Quantico, Virginia.
The defence requires closing the case on the grounds that Manning's detention conditions were cruel.
The U.S. military is accused of kidnapping several thousand secret documents.
On Friday, the indictment tried to prove that the plaintiff Bradley Manning, accused of the largest leak of classified material in U.S. history, did not take advantage of many opportunities to file a complaint about the ill-treatment that, according to him, he had to suffer.
During a cross-examination at a pre-trial hearing in Fort Meade, Maryland, military prosecutor Major Ashden Feyne stated that records of weekly visits to Manning by the representatives of the administration are a summary of the detention of the prison for nine months, not his detention in Quentin.
A cross-examination of Manning's application for protection on the grounds that the conditions of his detention were harsh and in itself sufficient punishment was carried out the day after Manning stated that while in custody, he intended to commit suicide.
A military intelligence analyst, who was arrested in June 2010, is accused of kidnapping several thousand secret documents while serving in Iraq.
These materials were subsequently published on the Internet on the WikiLeaks website.
WikiLeaks has not confirmed that the source of the information was Manning.
During Friday's hearing, Attorney Feyne and Manning reviewed the reports, which were completed after Manning's visits by administration officials during his time in the Quantico prison, where he was under strict detention from July 2010 to April 2011.
During the visits, prison officials asked Manning questions and recorded his answers.
When prosecutor Feyn asked about the reports on Friday, Manning admitted that he considered the administration’s handling of the prison as “excellent” and the general conditions of detention as “very professionally organized.”
The reviewed reports do not contain complaints of ill-treatment, despite Manning being asked directly about the terms of his detention, Feyn says.
Manning replied that he had expressed concern orally about these problems and that his visiting administration representatives had discussed these problems with him and stated that they would deal with them, but did not record it in writing.
“They recorded ‘problems are missing’ (after discussing my complaints), but that doesn’t mean I didn’t raise the issue in a conversation,” Manning said.
The military judge, Colonel Denise Linde, also asked Manning why he had not complained to him of ill-treatment in January 2011 during a meeting of the commission that considered the suicide intentions that he had expressed in writing a few months before.
Manning replied that during that meeting he wanted to get the “injury warning” regime removed from him and to ease the conditions of detention.
Representatives of the military leadership explained that the restricted detention regime - at a level lower than the surveillance regime for the purpose of preventing suicide - was introduced to protect the prisoner, as well as for the safety of others.
"I wanted to let the administration know that I'm okay with them canceling the trauma prevention regime... so that my standard of living improves, from my point of view," Manning said.
On Thursday, Manning testified about his arrest in Iraq and transfer to Kuwait, where he was detained for almost two months before being taken to prison at a naval base in Quantico, Virginia, in July 2010.
He reported that he had thoughts of suicide in Kuwait, and that one day he lost consciousness due to severe heat.
He explained that it is psychologically very difficult when you are not told how your fate is decided and what is going on in the outside world.
“My world has shrunk to the Camp-Arifjan base, to the size of my prison,” Manning said on Thursday.
“I thought I was going to die in this cage.”
While in Quantico, Manning, he said, spent most of his time in a small chamber—at least 21 hours, and often more than 23 hours a day—in complete solitude.
Manning reports that he was allowed to leave only mattresses, blankets, slippers, several items of clothing and glasses.
He says he tried to move because sleeping or even just lying down in the daytime was prohibited by the rules.
According to Manning, during his sleep, his eyes were constantly exposed to the light penetrating outside the camera.
If the guards did not see his face when he turned in bed at night, he said, he was woken up and forced to turn on his back.
Manning's lawyer filed a formal objection to the misappropriation of Manning in January 2011.
In April 2011, Manning was transferred to a military prison in Fort Levenworth, Kansas.
In addition, on Friday, the judge questioned Manning about the statement he made while giving testimony on Thursday, that after one night he was forced to sleep naked in his cell in Quantico, he was forced to stand naked in front of guards and other prisoners.
Manning said he did not have the opportunity to cover the blanket during the check.
Responding to the judge's questions on Friday, Manning said he understood from a guard's order that he should throw a blanket that could have been covered, but admitted that no one had directly ordered him to throw it.
On Thursday, Manning said he was forced to sleep naked the night before because of his attempt to show the officer that he posed no danger to himself.
Manning said he told the officer that he could use a rubber sock or slippers to hurt himself, but did not.
That night, according to Manning, his underwear, slippers and glasses were taken from the camera.
His lawyers hope that the judge will at least take into account what he had to live through during his imprisonment, and will significantly shorten his sentence in case Manning is found guilty by a military court that is due to begin hearing his case early next year.
The defense said it plans to propose to Manning to plead guilty to less serious crimes, and to challenge other charges as excessive.
The resumption of hearings is scheduled for this weekend, and the prosecution is expected to insist that conditions of detention were justified.
The Pentagon claims Manning was held in Quantico in accordance with rules regulating the detention of those arrested with the strictest regime possible.
The charges brought against Manning included aiding the enemy, illegally facilitating the disclosure of data on the Internet, the transfer of information relating to national defense, and the hijacking of state property or documents.
If he is convicted under all the provisions of the indictment, he may face life imprisonment.
My crisis of national self-determination is the story of an American of Mexican descent.
According to the author, many Mexicans were forced to leave Mexico because of the lack of opportunities to realize themselves.
Mexicans tend to blame those who have left because they remind the people of the country of difficult times.
Ruben Navarette believes that Mexicans of American descent are torn between two cultures.
During a recent trip to Mexico, I walked through the arrival corridor, approached the border control zone and froze on the spot.
The signs indicated two lines: one for Mexicanos (Mexicans), the other for Extranjeros (foreigners).
I stood in front of them for a few seconds, not knowing where to go.
I grew up in Central California, and I’ve been called a Mexican all my life.
It’s just a conditional name, just like my friends in Boston call themselves Irish, and friends in New York consider themselves Italian.
Later, I stopped at the complex construction of "American of Mexican origin."
But here I was in Mexico.
Here, in my grandfather’s homeland, there was no need for conditional names or complex constructions.
I was just an American.
I speak Spanish well enough to be able to ask questions or answer them.
But my vocabulary is poorer than that of speakers, and I can’t get rid of the American accent.
So I got my American passport and became in line for Extranjeros.
I recalled this story a few days ago when the re-elected President of Mexico, Enrique Pe<0xC3><0xB1>a Nieto, visited the White House and met with President Obama.
On the agenda of the meetings of the presidents of these countries were issues: immigration, drugs and trade.
President Pe<0xC3><0xB1>a Nieto was keen to talk about the rise of the Mexican economy, thanks to which Mexicans can now, with the same success, stay in Mexico instead of moving to the United States.
He wants to conclude a partnership agreement with the United States and Canada and create a North American trade bloc like the European Union.
In addition, President Pe<0xC3><0xB1>a Nieto promised to continue the war against drug cartels in Mexico, but no concrete proposals were made.
For Mexico, relations with the United States are a difficult and old-fashioned issue.
Most Americans never thought that in 1848 the United States invaded Mexico and, under the guise of a rifle, forced its leaders to give up half of their territory.
But Mexicans think for centuries, not minutes, and they see memories of those events in everything.
Therefore, it is only necessary for any U.S. statesman to speak at least a word of criticism towards Mexico, in the press and among the elites of Mexican society immediately spread complaints that Americans are infringing on the sovereignty of their neighbors.
And the descendants of Montesume are filled with militancy.
At the same time, the most difficult are the relations of Mexico with more than 35 million Americans of Mexican descent living in the United States.
Do you want to talk about abuse?
That's enough.
There are winners and losers in Mexico, people who find opportunities for themselves in this country, and those for whom there are no opportunities.
In Los Angeles, Las Vegas, Phoenix, Denver, or San Antonio, so many people of Mexican descent have only one reason: at some point in their family history, anyone - father or grandfather - had no right to realize themselves in Mexico and was forced to do so.
Most of the time, they were Mexicans of a certain type – sluggish, low-educated, from poor peasant families.
We are their descendants, and we remember it.
In Mexico, they see it differently.
Today, our life is an embodiment of the American dream, we studied in good schools and did good jobs, but we must not forget that even this dream is American, not Mexican.
Our national self-determination is confusing and unclear, but we know which country to consider as our own.
The United States of America.
In addition, we know that most of the representatives of the Mexican elite and the ruling class do not like us.
We answer them the same.
They see us as a reminder of humiliating defeats and treat us as second-class people, as unreal Mexicans.
We don’t speak Spanish well enough, and our ties with Mexico aren’t strong enough.
Our very existence for them is due to failures.
If our ancestors had succeeded in Mexico, they would not have left.
We wouldn’t be behind a silk curtain now, finding a full life in the United States, but losing our spiritual ties.
My wife was born in Guadalajara and legally moved to the United States as a child, and it reminds me that there are certain frictions between real Mexicans and Americans of Mexican descent - Mexicans understand their national identity more clearly.
She is a U.S. citizen and believes she belongs to both of these countries.
At the same time, many of my familiar Americans of Mexican descent do not feel belonging to any of them.
We listen to the Mexican band Los Tigres del Norte, but we also love Bruce Springsteen.
When you get the best of both worlds, you inevitably lose your roots.
In Mexico, we are Americans.
In the United States, we are called Mexicans.
Now, as I found out during my trip, as if our relationship hadn’t already been confusing enough, some Mexican leaders and intelligence representatives want to restore their relationship with the diaspora.
They want Mexican-Americans to work as Mexican ambassadors and represent their interests in the United States.
We could tell our American friends about what a beautiful country it is and how great it is to visit it, and we could convince political leaders to strengthen ties with Mexico.
Yeah, sure.
Nothing's gonna work out.
Too many insults in the past.
And given the gap between rich and poor, the spread of corruption and drug trafficking, many of us don’t think this country is so beautiful.
I'm sorry, but deal with it yourself, amigos.
And that's fair.
If some Mexicans still can’t forgive the United States for what they did to Mexico a century and a half ago, they will have to accept the fact that some Americans of Mexican descent are still offended by the way they were born in Mexico just recently.
Oh, yeah.
Maybe we have more in common than I thought.
The Old Battles in the New Middle East
The ceasefire agreement between Israel and Hamas could be a fragile foundation for the future of the world.
Is a long-term peace between the Arabs and the Israelis in the Middle East possible?
Another round of bloodshed pushes to the conclusion that such hopes are futile.
There are common, meaningless disputes about who first started; many of the buildings have been turned into ruins; more than 140 Palestinians have been killed, most of them civilians, and six Israelis have been displaced by Israelis; for the first time during the conflict, Israelis have been displaced from the territory.
However, despite the hopeless bonding of Israelis and Palestinians in their eternal conflict, changes have come to the Middle East.
This may be treated differently, but the events of the "Arab Spring" surrounded in a rebellious storm many established realities, and the Palestinians with the Israelis were unable to stay away from the whirlwind, which shocked the region.
Perhaps as a result, their struggle will become even more bloodthirsty than before.
However, there are reasons to hope for a way out of this deadly pitfall.
War without winners
At first glance, the situation does not give reason for optimism.
Even if the ceasefire, which was signed on November 21, will be implemented, the clashes that occurred this week only strengthened the positions of the security forces on both sides.
The leaders of the Islamist movement Hamas, which came to power in the Gaza Strip in 2007, say they have forced Israel to step down despite the losses they have suffered.
Despite the fact that some of the group’s leaders have been destroyed and 1.7 million residents are blocked in one of the most populous and troubled corners of our planet, Israel has failed to destroy Hamas.
In fact, Hamas is gaining popularity on the West Bank of the Jordan River – another Palestinian territory currently controlled by the more moderate Fatah movement.
Moreover, Hamas leaders may well come to the conclusion that time is working on them.
As the influence of Islamist movements in the Arab world grows, Hamas has new influential and wealthy friends.
Turkey, which was once Israel’s closest ally among Muslim countries, supported Hamas, followed by Qatar, one of the richest and most dynamically developing states in the Persian Gulf.
Hamas supporters claim the establishment of an Islamist crescent around Israel – from Lebanon in the north, which is ruled by Hezbollah’s militarized group, to Syria, where more and more pro-Islamist rebels are smashing the regime.
The most significant change in the balance of power in the region occurred on the southern borders of Israel, in the most populous and important Arab country, in Egypt, where under President Mohammed Mursi the influence of the Muslim Brotherhood movement was strengthened.
Hosni Mubarak, who ruled Egypt for 30 years and was overthrown in 2011, was a secular dictator who did not pay much attention to Hamas’s support.
The Muslim Brotherhood, on the contrary, is an organization much like Hamas, and their leaders are more prone to populism.
In future diplomatic arrangements, Hamas could become a significant player, whose voice will not be able to silence even Israel and America.
At the same time, supporters of the “hard” line in Israel will come to the opposite conclusion.
In a military sense, Hamas was defeated.
The Israeli anti-missile system Iron Dome justified the cost of its creation and successfully destroyed many of the rockets launched by Hamas.
The citizens of Israel can sleep calmly, at least for some time.
In terms of diplomacy, the United States remained true to its unchanging position; many European countries also blamed the start of the last round of violence against Hamas.
Another important factor is Israel’s economic prosperity, particularly under the Benjamin Netanyahu government, which largely ignored the peace process.
Despite the fact that since 2004, some 30 Israelis have been killed by rockets fired from the Gaza Strip, Israel has managed to minimize the problem of terrorists-killers, partly because of the wall that enters the territory of the West Bank of the Jordan River.
The position of Prime Minister Netanyahu, whose Likud party — as part of preparations for the January 22 elections — has united with even more aggressive conservatives under the leadership of Avigdor Lieberman, is very convenient.
What's the point of impoverishing the Palestinians and giving them their own state?
If we give them all the power in the West Bank, won’t they start launching rockets from there toward Israel, as their fellow Gazans do?
