Being bored in the world of electronic networks and constant connections is not so bad.
On this Thanksgiving day, I had to spend five hours at the airport, because our plane had mechanical malfunctions and it was replaced by another plane that we had been waiting for.
So I had enough time to think about the nature of boredom.
I won't fool you.
An afternoon at the airport waiting for a flight is really boring, and neither books, nor magazines, nor iPhones, nor even duty-free shops will help here.
However, more and more scientists and specialists in child development have recently expressed their support for boredom.
They say that in certain situations it is not so bad for us and for our children to miss.
This forces the brain to divert to interesting related topics, which may contribute to creativity.
And since in the modern world we are all constantly in front of some screen, the advantages of boredom pass us.
Do we need to get bored?
Oh, yeah.
And at the same time, it's not.
We'll get back to that.
In the past, I, like many, believed that boredom was an invention of relatively recent times, when people had more free time.
This is not the case, says Peter Tuy, a professor of Greek and Roman history at the University of Calgary in Canada, author of Boredom: A Lively History, Yale University Press, 2011.
“In fact, boredom can boast a very ancient history,” he says.
On the walls of Pompeii are found Latin inscriptions about boredom, dating from the first century.
The question remains as to how we understand boredom.
The problem is, says John D. Eastwood, assistant professor at the University of York in Ontario, Canada, that the understanding and vision of boredom has often changed.
After studying the research materials on the topic and asking a target group of 100 people, Professor Eastwood and his colleagues came to the following definition: boredom is when people “want but cannot do what would satisfy them.”
The difference between boredom and apathy, he says, is that a bored person does not do something he would like to do.
I don’t want to do anything with apathy.
The main thing about boredom, he says, is “a violation of attention and associated deterioration of mood and a feeling that time is slowing down.”
According to the description, boredom may seem very similar to depression.
However, Professor Eastwood argues that despite the possible link between these conditions, people who are bored see the causes of the problems in the world and the circumstances, and people who experience depression see the problems in themselves.
Sometimes we feel like we’re bored when we’re actually just having a hard time focusing on something.
In his study, “Unemployed Mind: Defining Toughness from the Point of View,” published in the September issue of the journal Perspectives on Psychological Science, Professor Eastwood and colleagues refer to a previous experiment, the participants of which were listening to the recording.
Some participants also heard loud sounds that were not related to the TV show included in the next room, others heard the same sounds at low volume, so that they could hardly be analyzed, and the third group listened only to the recording of the voice without a foreign ringtone.
Those participants who heard the low-volume TV noted that they were bored, more often others - they had difficulty concentrating, but they didn't know the reason for this and attributed it to boredom.
When we try to focus attention on a difficult or exciting task, interrupting attention can cause boredom, says Mark J. Fensk, an adjunct professor of neurology at the University of Gwell, Ontario, and one of the authors of the study.
On the other hand, when we do something uninteresting, "for example, by looking at the flow of products on a conveyor in search of marriage, distracting music can help avoid boredom."
It is believed, he continues, that when people start climbing on a chair or drawing caraculi on a sheet of paper, they do it out of boredom, but now we know that in fact such actions just help not to relax physically.
“The study showed that children who are not banned from scratching and spinning are better able to learn and memorize more information than children who are required to sit quietly,” Fensk said.
At some point, we all get bored: when a flight is delayed (as in my case), listening to a monotonous speech, watching an uninteresting movie.
However, different people show a different degree of propensity to boredom.
In the 1980s, to measure such individual characteristics, researchers developed a special “strain to boredom” scale.
To determine the assessment on such a scale use questions and affirmations, for example, "A lot of what I have to do is uniform and monotonous" or "I'm interested in too much, so there's no time for anything."
Using such questionnaires, the researchers determined that boys miss girls more often, says Steven Vodanovic, a professor of psychology at the University of West Florida, - especially in the presence of a variety of external irritants.
In general, however, teenagers are often bored.
In 1991, Reed Larson, a professor of personal and social development at the University of Illinois, conducted an experiment in which he contacted nearly 400 teenagers and their parents 7-8 times a day using a pager.
He received the following results: 32% of teenagers said they were bored in school and while doing homework, and 23% said they were bored outside of school.
Only 3% of parents said they were bored.
Professor Larson notes that he has no data on what such data about boredom would be now, 21 years later.
However, he knows that “the teenage age has a peak of propensity to boredom,” mainly because children and adolescents are not allowed to fully decide what to do.
Let’s get back to my original question: Is boredom useful?
Sometimes it doesn’t because in extreme manifestations, research shows, it can push people to absurd and dangerous physical actions, risky gambling, or abuse of certain substances in an attempt to get rid of boredom.
On the other hand, many philosophers and writers have been thinking about the connection between boredom and creativity, says Professor Vodanovich, who has devoted more than two decades to the study of this problem.
“So our brains tell us that we should do something else; that’s boring,” says Gary Marcus, a professor of psychology at the University of New York.
However, this very brain does not always know what is best to do.
If you get bored and you direct that energy to playing guitar or culinary experiences, you’ll do better.
However, if you start watching TV, you will only get better for a while, and soon it will pass.
Therefore, if your child is bored and you give him an iPad, he will stop being bored, but he will not learn to deal with boredom alone or in any other way to manage his time and employment,” says Professor Fensk.
“And such self-regulation skills are involved in a variety of situations,” he says.
Your child not only learns to do something on his own, he also learns to control himself in general.
I don't think we need to be bored in any way.
However, it is not worth considering something bad either.
Rather, you should learn to feel comfortable even outside of the continuous flow of action and technology.
Professor Eastwood agrees with that.
“We see it so that we need to experience boredom more often, while boredom is an extremely unpleasant, irresistible desire to do something meaningful,” he says.
In fact, people tend to somehow disconnect from constant worries and just relax.
“In the modern world, we are used to the constant overstimulation of the senses,” he says, “and when silence comes, we get lost and don’t know what to do.”
